On the Air: Clandestine Radiophonic Protest Groups in Italy, Switzerland, and Germany, 1976–77 -- t12: Kittler’s Sound -- t13: Clearing the Throat, Stumbling, and Coughing: An Anthropology of the Sonic Corpus according to Carlfriedrich Claus -- tPart V Sounds of the Present -- t14: Carsten Nicolai’s Art of Disturbance: Sound, Science, and Interference -- t15: Echoes of the Past: Sound in the History Museum -- t16: (Post)Digital Sounds: Acoustic Experiments in the Age of Algorithmic Processes -- tPart VI Epilogue -- t17: The Sound of Pine Needles Falling: The Art of Max Neuhaus -- tSelect Bibliography and Further Reading -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExplores sonic events and auditory experiences in German-speaking contexts from the Middle Ages to the digital age, opening up new understandings.As a sub-discipline of cultural studies, sound studies is a firmly established field of inquiry, examining how sonic events and auditory experiences unfold in culturally and historically contingent life situations.Responding to new questions in sound studies in the context of German-speaking cultures, and incorporating up-to-date methodologies, this Companion explores the significance of sound from the Middle Ages and the classical-romantic period through high-capitalist industrial modernity, the Nazi period and the Holocaust, and postwar Germany to the present digital age. The volume examines how sonic events are represented in literary fiction, radio productions, cinema, newsreels, documentaries, sound art, museum exhibitions, and other media, drawing for this inquiry on philosophy, aesthetics, literary criticism, musicology, art theory, and cultural studies. Each essay is a case study - of persons, events, and sonic, visual, or textual artifacts - situating them in wider contexts of culture, history, and politics. The volume not only revisits well-known topics from new angles, but seeks especially to explore neglected issues on the cultural periphery. It assembles original essays by leaders in the field and emerging scholars from the United States and Europe. Offering an advanced introduction to the topic, the Companion is addressed to anyone interested in how the analysis of sound phenomena opens up new understandings of German-speaking cultures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGermany-Intellectual life. 0aSound in popular culturezGermany. 0aSound in popular culture-Germany. 0aSoundxSocial aspects. 4aGerman Literature. 4aMusic. 4aPhilosophy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aaffective.  aagency.  aarticulation.  aattunement.  aaural.  aautonomy.  acognitive.  adigital.  adiscourse.  aexperiential.  aimmersion.  alistening.  amateriality.  aperception.  areception.  atechnology.  atemporality.  atransmission.  avoice.1 aAmmon, Frieder von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBromley, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClassen, Albrecht, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoebel, Rolf J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoebel, Rolf J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHeibach, Christiane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoegaerts, Josephine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJames H. Kopf, James M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKita, Caroline A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoepnick, Lutz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKopf, James M., econtributor.4ct